To achieve the desired layout where the pricing columns are displayed side by side on mobile devices, you can modify the code as follows:

```HTML
<section class="pricing">
  <div class="pricing-container">
    <div class="pricing-column column-mobile">
      <!-- Column 1 content -->
    </div>
    <div class="pricing-column column-mobile">
      <!-- Column 2 content -->
    </div>
    <div class="pricing-column column-mobile">
      <!-- Column 3 content -->
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
```

Then, you can add some CSS rules to display the columns side by side and enable swiping functionality:

```CSS
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  .pricing-container {
    display: flex;
    overflow-x: auto;
    scroll-snap-type: x mandatory;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
  }

  .pricing-column {
    flex: 1 0 100%;
    min-width: 300px;
    scroll-snap-align: start;
  }
}
```

Make sure to include this CSS code in the appropriate place within your stylesheet or HTML file. The media query with `max-width: 768px` specifies that these styles should only apply on screens with a maximum width of 768 pixels (typically mobile devices).

By doing this, the pricing columns will be displayed next to each other on mobile screens, and the visitor will be able to swipe horizontally to view different pricing plans. Adjust the `min-width` value in the CSS code if you want to change the minimum width of each pricing column on mobile devices.

Apologies for the confusion. You can keep the original class names "column-1", "column-2", and "column-3" if you prefer.

Regarding the CSS, please try adding `!important` to the relevant properties to ensure they override any conflicting styles. Here's an updated version of the CSS:

```CSS
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  .pricing-container {
    display: flex !important;
    overflow-x: auto !important;
    scroll-snap-type: x mandatory !important;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch !important;
  }

  .pricing-column {
    flex: 1 0 100% !important;
    min-width: 300px !important;
    scroll-snap-align: start !important;
  }
}
```

Please make sure to add this CSS code in the appropriate place within your stylesheet or HTML file. The `!important` declaration should give higher specificity and ensure that the styles are applied correctly. Let me know if you're still experiencing any issues.
